New Rules for the World Economy
CAMBRIDGE, MASS.: Let us assume that the world's leading politicians would once again meet in Bretton Woods, New Hampshire, to design a new world economic order.
Of course, they would primarily deal with today's problems: the crisis in the Eurozone, global recovery, financial regulation, international macroeconomic imbalances, etc. However, addressing these issues would force the assembled leaders to go beyond them and reconsider the stability of the overall world economic arrangements.
Here are seven principles for global economic governance based on sound common sense, on which they might possibly agree.
(I discuss these in more detail in my new book, The Globalization Paradox.)
1. The markets must be deeply embedded in existing control systems.
The idea that markets regulate themselves has suffered a fatal blow due to the recent financial crisis and should be buried forever.
Markets need other societal institutions that support them.
They rely on courts, legal systems, and regulatory bodies that establish and enforce rules.
They depend on the stabilizing functions provided by central banks and countercyclical fiscal policy.
They need the political acceptance generated by redistributive taxation, safety nets, and social insurance.
And all of this applies equally to global markets.
2. For the foreseeable future, democratic state governance will largely be organized within national political communities.
The nation-state lives on, even if it may be somewhat faltering, and remains essentially the only game in town.
The pursuit of a world government is a futile love affair.
It is hardly to be expected that national governments will cede significant control powers to transnational institutions; furthermore, a harmonization of rules would not benefit societies with different needs and preferences.
The European Union could be the only exception to this axiom, although its current crisis rather seems to confirm it.
Too often we waste international cooperation on overly ambitious goals. In the end, weak results emerge that represent the smallest common denominator between the large countries.
When international cooperation is "successful," it produces rules that are either toothless or reflect the preferences of the more powerful countries.
The Basel rules on capital requirements and the World Trade Organization rules on subsidies, intellectual property, and investment measures typify this kind of excessive ambition.
We can strengthen the efficiency and legitimacy of globalization by supporting democratic procedures in our own country, instead of undermining them.

3. Pluralistic Prosperity: The acknowledgment that the central institutional infrastructure of the world economy must be built at the national level gives individual countries the freedom to develop institutions that best meet their needs.
The USA, Europe, and Japan have generated comparable prosperity in the long term.
Yet their labor markets, corporate governance, antitrust regulations, social safety nets, and financial systems differ significantly, and a sequence of these "models" – a different one each decade – is then presented as the great success that others should emulate.
The most successful societies of the future will allow space for experiments and allow further evolution of their institutions.
A world economy that recognizes the necessity and value of institutional diversity will foster rather than suppress such experimental enthusiasm and evolutionary development.
4. Countries have the right to protect their own rules and institutions.
The aforementioned principles may appear innocuous.
But they carry powerful implications that clash with the prevailing opinion of globalization supporters.
Such an implication is the right of individual countries to protect their national institutional decisions.
The recognition of institutional diversity would be meaningless if countries did not have the instruments available to shape and preserve their own institutions – in one word: to "protect" them.
We should therefore accept that countries may retain national rules – tax policy, financial regulation, labor standards or rules for the protection of consumer health and safety – and that they may do so by setting up barriers at their borders, if trade demonstrably threatens indigenous practices that enjoy broad support among the population.
If the advocates of globalization are right, the call for such protective measures will fail due to a lack of evidence or support.
If they are wrong, there is a safety valve so that conflicting values – the advantages of open economies and the advantages of maintaining national regulations – can both receive due attention in public debates.
5. Countries have no right to impose their own institutions on others.
The use of restrictions in cross-border trade or in the financial sector to maintain values and rules in their own country should not be confused with their use to impose these values and rules on other countries.
The rules of globalization should not force Americans or Europeans to consume goods produced in a way that most citizens in these countries find unacceptable.
Similarly, they should not allow the USA or the EU to use trade sanctions or other pressure measures to change labor market rules, environmental policy, or financial regulation in other countries.
Countries have a right to difference, not to forced convergence.

6. International Economic Agreements for Regulating the Interaction between National Institutions: Relying on national states to provide the basic control functions of the world economy does not mean that we should abandon international rules.
The Bretton Woods system finally also had clear rules, even if these were limited in scope and depth.
A complete catch-as-catch-can approach would benefit no one.
What we need are traffic rules for the world economy that help vehicles of different sizes, shapes, and speeds to pass each other, rather than prescribing an identical car or a uniform speed limit.
We should strive to achieve a maximum level of globalization that is in harmony with the preservation of space for diversity in national institutional arrangements.
7. Undemocratic countries cannot count on the same rights and privileges in the international economic order as democracies.
What gives the aforementioned principles their attractiveness and legitimacy is that they are based on democratic consultation - where this actually takes place, within the nation-states.
If states are not democratic, this framework collapses.
We can then no longer assume that their institutional arrangements reflect the preferences of their citizens.
Other, less permissive rules must apply to undemocratic states.
These are the principles that the architects of the next world economic order must accept.
Most importantly, they must accept the ultimate paradox that each of these principles illustrates: globalization works best when it is not taken too far.
